%[text] #  CBCT Reconstruction Pipeline: FDK → IR → DL Refinement
%[text] This Live Script demonstrates a complete cone‑beam CT (CBCT) reconstruction workflow using three stages:
%[text] 1. **FDK Reconstruction** – classical analytical Feldkamp–Davis–Kress method
%[text] 2. **Iterative Reconstruction (IR)** – noise‑reduced refinement from sparse/noisy projections
%[text] 3. **Deep-Learning Reconstruction (DL)** – learned enhancement model for high‑quality output \
%[text] Each stage takes the output of the previous step, enabling a clean, modular pipeline.
%[text] ## 1️⃣ FDK Reconstruction
%[text] *Analytical Cone-Beam CT Reconstruction*
%[text] The **Feldkamp–Davis–Kress (FDK)** algorithm is the classical analytic method used for circular CBCT trajectories. It is fast and provides a good baseline reconstruction, especially when projections are not too sparse.
%[text] **Purpose:**
%[text] - Ramp-filter projections
%[text] - Perform geometric backprojection
%[text] - Produce an initial 3‑D volume reconstruction \

vol = reconFDK('CT_low.mat', 'Verbose', true); %[output:567c7d03]
%[text] **Output:**
%[text] - `vol` — reconstructed 3‑D volume (typically single precision)
%[text] - Useful as a baseline for further enhancement via IR or DL methods \
%%
%[text] ## 2️⃣ Iterative Reconstruction (IR)
%[text] *Physics-Based Noise Reduction and Artifact Suppression*
%[text] Iterative reconstruction incorporates a forward model and regularization (e.g., TV, edge-preserving penalties).
%[text] It typically improves:
%[text] - Low-dose or sparse-view reconstructions
%[text] - Streak artifacts
%[text] - Noise characteristics
%[text] - Edge sharpness \
%[text] **Inputs:**
%[text] - The original projection data (`CT_low.mat`)
%[text] - The analytic FDK reconstruction (`FDK_low.mat`) \
vol = reconIR('CT_low.mat','FDK_low.mat', 'Verbose', true); %[output:42a81f8d]
%[text] **Output:**
%[text] - `vol_ir` — improved reconstruction with reduced noise and streak artifacts
%[text] - Often used as the target reference for training DL models \
%%
%[text] ## 3️⃣ Deep-Learning Reconstruction (DL)
%[text] *Learned Hybrid Enhancement (FDK → IR → DL)*
%[text] This stage applies a trained neural network that learns to map:
%[text] **FDK → Iterative Reconstruction (IR) quality**
%[text] The DL model captures subtle structures and removes residual artifacts that physics-only IR cannot.
%[text] **Inputs:**
%[text] - `FDK_low.mat`: Contains the baseline FDK reconstruction
%[text] - `Hybrid_IR_low.mat`: Contains the improved IR reconstruction (target)
%[text] - Variable names describing which fields hold FDK and IR volumes \
[yPredVol, net] = reconDL('FDK_low.mat', 'Hybrid_IR_low.mat', ... %[output:group:7b6add82] %[output:6ce6b111] %[output:76ccc611] %[output:2b163a84]
    'FDKVar','FDKvol', 'TGTVar','hybridIR_vol', ... %[output:6ce6b111] %[output:76ccc611] %[output:2b163a84]
    'OutRoot','cbct_run_low'); %[output:group:7b6add82] %[output:6ce6b111] %[output:76ccc611] %[output:2b163a84]
%[text] **Output:**
%[text] - `yPredVol` — DL‑enhanced reconstruction
%[text] - `net` — the trained neural network (for reuse/evaluation) \
%[text] ## 🔚 Summary of the Pipeline
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | **Stage** | **Function** | **Purpose** | **Output** |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | 1\. FDK | `reconFDK` | Fast analytic baseline | `FDKvol` |
%[text] | 2\. IR | `reconIR` | Physics-based enhancement | `hybridIR_vol` |
%[text] | 3\. DL | `reconDL` | Learned refinement | `yPredVol` |
%[text:table]
%[text] Together, these methods provide a complete and modular reconstruction chain suitable for:
%[text] - Sparse-view CBCT
%[text] - Low-dose scans
%[text] - Research prototyping
%[text] - DL training/evaluation workflow \
%%
%[text] # 4. Visualization and Hounsfield Unit Mapping
%[text] This section converts the reconstructed CBCT volume into **Hounsfield Units (HU)** and visualizes it using MATLAB’s **Medical Imaging Toolbox**. The workflow includes:
%[text] - Deriving HU calibration (air/water reference)
%[text] - Creating a `medicalVolume` with correct voxel geometry
%[text] - Performing smoothing and window/level adjustments
%[text] - Using `volshow` with cinematic rendering for high‑quality 3‑D visualization \
%[text] ## 4.1 Converting Reconstruction Output to Hounsfield Units (HU)
%[text] CBCT systems typically output arbitrary reconstruction units. To bring your volume into a **clinically meaningful scale**, we map:
%[text] - **Air → –1000 HU**
%[text] - **Water → 0 HU** \
%[text] Because not all datasets provide calibration masks, we use an **intensity percentile estimate** (1st and 99th percentiles) as approximate references.
% === Inputs ===
reconImage = double(yPredVol);     % ensure double for math

% Option A: Prefer ROI-derived means for air/water (recommended)
% airVal   = mean(reconImage(airMask), 'omitnan');
% waterVal = mean(reconImage(waterMask), 'omitnan');

% Option B: If you don't have masks, use percentiles instead of min/max
p = [1 99];
prc = prctile(reconImage(:), p);
airVal   = prc(1);   % rough "air-like" signal
waterVal = prc(2);   % rough "water-like" signal

% Safety checks
if ~isfinite(airVal) || ~isfinite(waterVal)
    error('Non-finite air/water reference values. Check reconImage or masks.');
end
if abs(waterVal - airVal) < eps
    error('airVal and waterVal are too close. Provide better references/ROIs.');
end

% Linear HU mapping: air → -1000 HU, water → 0 HU
slope     = 1000 / (waterVal - airVal);
intercept = -1000 - slope * airVal;

% Compute HU, handle NaNs gracefully
volumeHU = slope * reconImage + intercept;
volumeHU(~isfinite(volumeHU)) = NaN;

% Optional: clip to a reasonable HU range to suppress extreme artifacts
clipRange = [-1200, 3000];  % adjust per scanner/protocol
volumeHU = min(max(volumeHU, clipRange(1)), clipRange(2));

% Optional: cast to int16 for conventional storage/visualization
volumeHU_int16 = int16(round(volumeHU));

%%
%[text] ## 4.2 Creating a Medical Imaging Toolbox Volume
%[text] To visualize using cinematic rendering, we create a `medicalVolume` object that includes voxel spacing and a patient‑compatible coordinate system (LPS+).
% === Medical Imaging Toolbox: geometry and patient coordinate system ===
R = medicalref3d(size(volumeHU_int16));

% IMPORTANT: Set voxel sizes and origin if you know them
% R.PixelExtentInWorldX = dx_mm;
% R.PixelExtentInWorldY = dy_mm;
% R.PixelExtentInWorldZ = dz_mm;
% R.ImageExtentInWorldX/Y/Z are then implied; set R.WorldLimits or R.XWorldLimits, etc.,
% if you need explicit bounds.

% Create medical volume and set patient coordinate system
medVolReconImage = medicalVolume(volumeHU_int16, R);
medVolReconImage.VolumeGeometry.PatientCoordinateSystem = "LPS+";
%%
% Optional sanity prints
fprintf('HU mapping: slope=%.6f, intercept=%.6f\n', slope, intercept); %[output:5b6410e8]
fprintf('AirVal=%.6g → -1000 HU, WaterVal=%.6g → 0 HU\n', airVal, waterVal); %[output:4d830f37]
%[text] This ensures:
%[text] - Consistent spatial scaling
%[text] - Correct anatomical orientation
%[text] - Compatibility with clinical visualization workflows \
%[text] ## 
%%
% Given: slope = 1171.154553; intercept = -1036.589915;
volHU = slope* medVolReconImage.Voxels + intercept;

volHU_clean = imgaussfilt3(volHU, 1.5);
alpha = zeros(256,1);
alpha(120:256) = linspace(0,1,137);
voltemp = volshow(volHU_clean, ...
    RenderingStyle="CinematicRendering", ...
    Colormap=bone(256), ...
    DisplayRange=[50 1800], ...   % bone window
    Alphamap=alpha);  % soft tissue→transparent, bone→opaque
viewer = voltemp.Parent;
viewer.BackgroundColor = [0 0.2 0.6]; %[output:4a82992d]
%[text] ##  Summary of Visualization Stage
%[text] 1. Convert reconstruction intensities → **Hounsfield Units**
%[text] 2. Build a **medicalVolume** with correct voxel spacing
%[text] 3. Smooth the data for clean cinematic appearance
%[text] 4. Visualize using `volshow` with full control over shading, color, and opacity \
%[text] This creates a professional, radiology-grade rendering of your reconstructed CBCT volume.
%%
%[text] # ⚡ 5. CUDA Code Generation & GPU-Accelerated Visualization
%[text] This section shows how to **generate CUDA code** for the FDK reconstructor using **GPU Coder**, build a **CUDA MEX**, run it on your **600×600×360** dataset, and then **visualize** the reconstructed volume. The FFT filtering is mapped to **cuFFT** in the generated MEX, while backprojection runs on CPU (as designed).
%[text] ## 5.1 Generate CUDA MEX with GPU Coder
%[text] We first configure GPU Coder, specify **fixed input sizes** (for maximum performance), and compile the entry point `reconFDK_codegen` into a CUDA MEX.
cfg = coder.gpuConfig('mex');
cfg.GenerateReport = true;

P_arg      = coder.typeof(single(0), [600 600 360], [false false false]);
angles_arg = coder.typeof(single(0), [1 360],       [false false]);

sf   = coder.typeof(single(0));
si32 = coder.typeof(int32(0));
sl   = coder.typeof(false);

filterConst = coder.Constant('ramp');
Nf_fftConst = coder.Constant(int32(1024));   % <= power-of-two for cuFFT stability

args = { ...
  P_arg, angles_arg, ...
  sf, sf, sf, sf, sf, sf, ...                 % DSD, DSO, du, dv, u0, v0
  sf, sf, sf, si32, si32, si32, ...           % dx, dy, dz, nx, ny, nz
  filterConst, Nf_fftConst, sf, si32, sl, sl  % padFactor, batchZ, useGPU, verbose
};

codegen -config cfg reconFDK_codegen -args args %[output:2153b919]
%[text] **Notes:**
%[text] - Use `'mex'` for rapid iteration in MATLAB; switch to `'lib'` for a **CUDA library** to integrate elsewhere.
%[text] - `Nf_fftConst = int32(2048)` corresponds to `nu=600`, `padFactor=2` → `2^nextpow2(1200)=2048`.
%[text] - If you change `nu` or `padFactor`, update `Nf_fftConst` and rebuild. \
%%
%[text] ## 5.2 Run the CUDA MEX on Your CBCT Data
%[text] Load your `.mat` inputs, match types/shapes, and call the generated MEX. This will perform **GPU-accelerated FFT filtering** via cuFFT and reconstruct the 3‑D volume.
%% Load & prep inputs
S = load('CT_low.mat');

P          = single(S.P);                       % [nu,nv,nViews] e.g., [600,600,360]
angles_rad = single(S.angles_rad(:).');         % [1,nViews] row
DSD        = single(S.DSD);  DSO = single(S.DSO);
du         = single(S.du);   dv  = single(S.dv);
u0         = single(S.u0_pixels); v0 = single(S.v0_pixels);

% Recon grid (example: 0.5 mm voxels → 300×300×180 mm => 600×600×360)
dx = single(0.5); dy = single(0.5); dz = single(0.5);
nx = int32(600);  ny = int32(600);  nz = int32(360);

% Controls (memory-safe choices)
filter_type = 'ramp';         % 'ramp' | 'hamming' | 'shepp-logan'
Nf_fft      = int32(1024);    % >= nu ; power-of-two suggested
padFactor   = single(1);      % informational (Nf_fft dictates effective FFT length)
batchZ      = int32(8);       % smaller → less memory (e.g., 8 or 16)
useGPU      = true;           % MEX: cuFFT used automatically; false to test CPU path
verbose     = false;

%% Call the CUDA MEX
tic;
FDKvol = reconFDK_codegen_mex( ...
    P, angles_rad, DSD, DSO, du, dv, u0, v0, ...
    dx, dy, dz, nx, ny, nz, filter_type, ...
    Nf_fft, padFactor, batchZ, useGPU, verbose);
t = toc;

fprintf('MEX done in %.3f s. Volume [%d %d %d]\n', t, size(FDKvol)); %[output:6de77988]
%%
%[text] # 5.3 Visualize the Reconstructed CBCT Volume
%[text] After reconstructing the 3D CBCT volume using the CUDA‑accelerated MEX function, we can visualize the results to inspect the image quality and anatomical structures. MATLAB provides several convenient tools for interactive volume exploration.
%[text] A simple and effective option is to use **`sliceViewer`**, which allows you to scroll through axial, sagittal, or coronal slices. The viewer can be launched directly with the reconstructed volume:
fig = uifigure('Name','CBCT Visualization');
panel = uipanel(fig, 'Position',[20 20 600 600]);

sliceViewer(FDKvol, 'Parent', panel, 'Colormap', gray);
%%
%[text] For quick inspection in script‑based workflows, you can also display three orthogonal slices:
figure; %[output:5964f851]
subplot(1,3,1); imagesc(FDKvol(:,:,round(end/2))); axis image off; colormap gray; title('Axial'); %[output:5964f851]
subplot(1,3,2); imagesc(squeeze(FDKvol(:,round(end/2),:))'); axis image off; colormap gray; title('Sagittal'); %[output:5964f851]
subplot(1,3,3); imagesc(squeeze(FDKvol(round(end/2),:,:))'); axis image off; colormap gray; title('Coronal'); %[output:5964f851]

